The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 L amp;T profit rises 50% to Rs 701cr

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Naik: Building hopes

 Mumbai, May 29: Larsen amp; Toubro has posted a 50 per cent rise in net profit for the fourth quarter ended March 31, 2007, at Rs 700.77 crore compared with Rs 466.85 crore in the corresponding period of the previous year. 

 L amp;Ts total income for the quarter shot to Rs 6,452.38 crore from Rs 4,782.46 crore in the year-ago period. For the year ended March 31, the company posted an increase of 39 per cent in net profit (after extraordinary items) at Rs 1,403.02 crore against Rs 1,012.14 crore a year ago. Total income rose to Rs 18,041.13 crore in 2006-07 from Rs 15,198.63 crore in 2005-06.

 Strong economic fundamentals, a buoyant market, growing capital goods sector and appropriate business opportunities contributed to the companys robust growth in revenue and profitability.

 The board of directors of L amp;T today recommended a final dividend of Rs 2 per equity share. This takes the total dividend for the year, including the interim dividend of Rs 11 per share, to Rs 13 per equity share. 

 The engineering and construction segment reported a 37 per cent growth in its order book position at Rs 25,249 crore during 2006-07 because of an increased activity in the hydrocarbon amp; infrastructure sectors, both at home and abroad. The share of international orders was 27 per cent of the total inflow. 

 amp;t chairman amp; managing director A.M. Naik said power would be a major thrust area for the company this fiscal and it planned to spend about Rs 2,500 crore as capital expenditure this year.

 India is a power deficit country and keeping that in view, amp;t would be concentrating on power, Naik said. The company is planning to set up super critical boilers and super critical turbines plant in the country to generate power.

 HPCL net

 State-run Hindustan Petroleum Corp today announced a 72.7 per cent dip in net profit for the fourth quarter ended March 31 at Rs 549.54 crore compared with Rs 2,013.41 crore in the corresponding quarter last fiscal.

 Total income, however, rose 5.3 per cent to Rs 22,045.94 crore from Rs 20,943.15 crore in the year-ago period. The board of directors has recommended a final dividend of 120 per cent in addition to the interim dividend of 60 per cent paid in December 2006.

 The company posted a four-fold increase in net profit at Rs 1,571.17 crore for 2006-07.




